Changing trends in trade linkages in the world today have widened the impact of Covid-19 on global output and reshaped the paths to recovery. 
Intra-African trade represents a small portion of the continent’s total trade. According to data from UNCTADStat, over the period 2010–2019, the share of intra-African exports of goods in Africa’s total export averaged 15 per cent while comparative regional figures for the Americas were 55 per cent, Asia 60 per cent, and Europe enjoys the highest share at 69 per cent. 





In terms of imports, intra-African trade amounts to 14 per cent of the continent’s imports, compared to much higher values for America (41 per cent), Asia (62 per cent) and Europe (66 per cent). 
Africa’s dependence on external markets for basic foods, medicinal and pharmaceutical products is particularly acute.  From 2010 to 2019, Africa imported on average about 95 per cent of its pharmaceutical product needs from the rest of the world. The equivalent figure for basic food products was 85 per cent. 
At the same time, Africa’s prospects for Foreign Direct Investment (FDI), which remains an important source of financing across the developing world, is gloomy for the continent. According to the UNCTAD Investments Trends Monitor released in October 2020,  FDI inflows to Africa declined by 28 per cent in the first half of 2020.



