The consequences are that Africa needs to look local and regional today more than ever before.
Higher vulnerability
The Covid-19 outbreak and its induced restrictions suggest that dependence on remote markets increases vulnerabilities during periods of global crisis ─ such as the current health pandemic ─ which tend to lead to supply disruptions. In contrast, shorter supply chains are more likely to reduce those vulnerabilities. 
Today, Africa’s top imports, mainly sourced from the rest of the world, include agro-processed products (rice, milk, sugar); manufactured base metals (cathodes and tubes, iron and steel bars), wood, textiles and rubber products, petroleum oil and its by-products, medicinal and pharmaceutical goods. 
Most of these goods could potentially be manufactured across the continent, given Africa’s resource endowments. Yet, the fragmentation of African markets and persistent bottlenecks to trade have impeded the emergence and development of regional value chains.  Impediments to regional trade include several non-tariffs barriers such as cumbersome customs procedures and other border inefficient processes and practices including numerous and incoherent regulatory requirements. UNCTAD estimates that ad valorem equivalents of non-tariffs measures in Africa can be as high as 14 per cent for vegetables, 11.4 per cent for beverages and tobacco, 11.3 per cent for machinery and 11.1 per cent for optical and medical devices.



