Recent estimates from the World Bank suggest that the AfCFTA by 2035, could boost Africa’s total exports by 29 per cent, intra-continental trade by more than 81 per cent and Africa exports to the rest of the world by 19 per cent, with most of the gains accrued to the manufacturing sector. This will help increase real income of the continent by nearly $450 billion, while lifting an additional 30 and 68 million people respectively from extreme and moderate poverty.
Implementation of the AfCFTA could support continental efforts to build a stronger pharmaceutical sector by increasing its reliance on local and regional industries. This is essential for building greater resilience of Africa’s health sector to future pandemics.



