Countries such as South Africa, Kenya, Ghana, Egypt, and Nigeria – to cite a few – have local industrial capacities to manufacture medicines for export to African markets, especially for generic and essential medicines. This will certainly require a more conducive policy environment in step with the AfCFTA framework, with attractive investment policies and regional medicines procurement; ease of access to resources including skills, and finance; harmonization of health and pharmaceutical regulatory frameworks at regional and continental levels. 
In this regard, UNCTAD and the WHO are collaborating on a three-year project to help build the required partnerships and guide governments on the policies required to boost the local production of essential medicines in the East African Community (EAC) and Ethiopia.
Covid-19 has delayed the start of first trading under the AfCFTA, previously planned for 1st July 2020 and now expected for January 2021. Yet, challenges faced during the outbreak of the pandemic and lessons learned suggest that momentum has to be maintained behind the implementation of the AfCFTA for deeper regional integration to build the resilience of African economies to future health crises.



