}



However, implementing the AfCFTA requires significant amounts of financial resources at a time when Africa is being buffeted by Covid-19. It is therefore essential for the continent to secure funding from all sources to ensure the Agreement is implemented despite the challenging context resulting from the pandemic. Combatting Illicit financial flows for example which deprive the continent of more than $88.6 billion every year could contribute to supporting the implementation of priorities towards the realization of the AfCFTA.
Putting Africa’s behind the border Agenda into national and regional perspectives, requires efforts from all stakeholders, with an interest in the development of African economies.
These range from governments, the private sector including multinationals operating across the continent, development banks (including AfDB and Afreximbank), the regional economic commissions, the African Union Commission, development partners including UN agencies and programmes, and most importantly every single African citizen.



